  "slug": "were-debating-the-lion-king-in-2019-why-exit-survey",
  "title": "We’re Debating ‘The Lion King’ in 2019. Why? | Exit Survey",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2019-07-19",
  "runtimeMin": 61,
  "format": "Sean and Amanda review Jon Favreau's photorealistic Lion King remake against the 1994 original: the visuals, a script nobody bothered to rewrite, a voice cast that only sometimes works, and where all of it lands at the Oscars. Plus, a run through Favreau's directing career from Swingers to Iron Man.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The Lion King, 2019 vs. 1994",
      "note": "the remake against the original",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Lion King (2019)",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Directed by Jon Favreau, with Rob Legato overseeing the photorealistic digital animation. Thirty minutes longer than the original but running on a script that was never rewritten for the new format; the extra time mostly goes to a genuinely scary new hyena chase. James Earl Jones reprises Mufasa note for note; Billy Eichner and Seth Rogen (Timon and Pumbaa) are the best part of the movie; Chiwetel Ejiofor's Scar is too dignified for the camp Jeremy Irons brought; Donald Glover's older Simba is flat; Beyoncé's Nala doesn't work as a vocal performance. Sean is won over by the visuals; Amanda finds it inert without the original's more stylized, physical musical numbers. Expected to compete for Best Visual Effects and Best Original Song, with a harder path into Best Animated Feature behind Toy Story 4."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Lion King (1994)",
          "year": 1994,
          "note": "Nominated for two Oscars (original score and \"Can You Feel the Love Tonight\" for original song), back before there was a Best Animated Feature category. Amanda's entry point into Elton John, and, both hosts agree, the peak of Disney's '90s renaissance: no princess, no central love story, Shakespeare and the Joseph/Moses story underneath a kids' cartoon. Voice highlights include Jeremy Irons's campy Scar, James Earl Jones's Mufasa, Nathan Lane, and Rowan Atkinson. The animated \"Hakuna Matata\" number choreographs its characters like a Busby Berkeley routine, something the hosts say the remake's more naturalistic staging can't touch."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Jon Favreau's Career, Before The Lion King",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Swingers",
          "year": 1996,
          "note": "Favreau wrote and starred, directed by Doug Liman; his breakthrough, made with Vince Vaughn."
        },
        {
          "title": "Made",
          "year": 2001,
          "note": "Favreau's directorial debut and a Swingers reunion with Vince Vaughn; Sean singles out a great Diddy performance."
        },
        {
          "title": "Elf",
          "year": 2003,
          "note": "Became a classic almost immediately."
        },
        {
          "title": "Zathura: A Space Adventure",
          "year": 2005,
          "note": "Underperformed at the box office."
        },
        {
          "title": "Iron Man",
          "year": 2008,
          "note": "Arguably the most important movie of the century regardless of how you feel about comic-book movies: it set the template for the genre."
        },
        {
          "title": "Iron Man 2",
          "year": 2010,
          "note": "The weak link in the run, by Sean's own admission."
        },
        {
          "title": "Cowboys & Aliens",
          "year": 2011,
          "note": "Not good, despite a stacked cast: Harrison Ford, Daniel Craig, Olivia Wilde, Sam Rockwell."
        },
        {
          "title": "Chef",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "A small, personal palate-cleanser after Cowboys & Aliens, with Favreau back in front of the camera."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Jungle Book (2016)",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "Its unpredictable billion-dollar gross is, per Sean, the reason The Lion King exists at all."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
